This painting gives the essence of Goddess Durga in a folk art style which shows a lot of details and bright colors but the painting area seems congested and does not let the artist give equal attention to every part of it.

It look so rural with its natural colors and the dotes of traditional costumes that were used on the people; however, the facial expressions could have been given more details so the feelings of the characters could be clearly seen.
The painting is in general complete with folk art style, bright clothes colours and the mise-en-scène, but the faces are similar to each other.
The painting depicts a divine scene on water and the use of color is rather fair, however the facial and body language should be more detailed to capture the events.
The displayed image is pretty good. All the Hindu gods are displayed in a beautiful way.
It depicts a moment of fighting and dancing with a realistic brutish folk-art taste, though the positions of the fighters could be chosen more appropriate to convey an effect of the battle.

The painting is quite rich in different aspects of rural life and spirituality, symbolism; however, the composition looks a bit cluttered, and, therefore, it is challenging to pay attention to some details.

The painting provides an excellent representation of Goddess Durga slaying the demon, with most details and colors being as vibrant as possible, but a degree of clutter detracts from the overall scenery.
The dramatic and ritualistic tension in the first painting create interest, though the faces must be more expressive.
The serene picture of the divine from a lotus is pleasing to the eye, but the faces must be more detailed for more depth.
The royal figure within the palace is nicely composed with rich color but additional pose variation would generate dynamism.
The goddess's powerful stance and symbolic imagery are effective, but the environment is somewhat sparse.
The ritual gathering is full of life and color, though the subjects are somewhat redundant in pose.
The dynamic movement and rich color contrast in the first painting make it a fascinating view, though the faces are not expressive enough.
The heavenly figure and royal background in the second painting are well done, but facial expressions are a bit rigid.
The natural background in the third painting nicely illustrates rural life, though the characters' poses are not as varied.
The fourth one has a lively village scene with active body language, but the repeated postures make it less energetic.
The novel viewpoint in the fifth one, with a big animal, introduces curiosity, but the composition is slightly off-balance.
The close-up village interaction in the sixth one is rich visually, though the background features are not so fine.
The story in the seventh painting, which includes nature and human interaction, is intriguing, but the floating face appears unnatural.
The enchanting depiction in the eighth painting, with an overgrown bird, is a captivating story, though the size appears exaggerated.
The eerie contrast between the human-like figures and the creatures from a dream provides the piece with a haunting atmosphere, though some elements seem excessive.
The dark, single-color tone does an excellent job of evoking mystery and suspense in the piece, though the single face makes the figures seem uniform
The multiple heads provide the piece with a mythological aura, though the symmetry makes it seem slightly rigid.
The earth-toned and black color scheme is eye-catching, but the same pose for the characters reduces the sense of action.
The fight is intense and dramatic, with flying arrows adding energy, though more variety in facial expressions would introduce emotion.
Floating heads and seated characters create a visually appealing composition, but the perspective appears somewhat flattened.
The animal-human hybrid is a curious visual element, but the simplicity of the background makes it appear disconnected from the rest of the work
